<subSubSection id="91DE029B96469F98449F89AC2CE88019" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="distribution and biology">
<paragraph id="A68C20C476CEA292ADE3DB0A82F153BD" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Distribution and biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8E9D6B032FCC64FF764DBD6132115EF" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
It has to be pointed out that 
<taxonomicName id="01083FBE599736B9B02586768D100892" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="35E8AFE16BF160DB96C4B5428B79F6BC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much less broadly distributed as previously thought. Indeed, its distribution is restricted to a narrow strip in the northeast of Madagascar ranging from Makirovana and Ambondrobe north to Montagne des 
<normalizedToken id="30651F48DDB609C432EC5DE4F5AEE931" originalValue="Français">Francais</normalizedToken>
. Most of the remaining locality data listed under 
<taxonomicName id="B116C40F435BE72C9DD7F2E49586C460" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="6B35D530B2120FAAF932958960CD94D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="32CA07071090283EE93255E8D4147858" author="Fisher, BL" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="146 - 152" refId="B7" refString="Fisher, BL, 2007. A new species of Probolomyrmex from Madagascar. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 80: 146 - 152" title="A new species of Probolomyrmex from Madagascar" volume="80" year="2007">Fisher 2007</bibRefCitation>
) are actually records of the new species 
<taxonomicName id="2C31A434B32A08214611BA5A4CF8E208" authorityName="Hita Garcia &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex curculiformis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curculiformis">
<emphasis id="E5D9FA5602E3480FA7A583561A0267BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex curculiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except for Manongarivo. The only available specimen from the latter locality is damaged, and it cannot be assigned to any species. Therefore, we do not list this locality for 
<taxonomicName id="FF0022A13ABEB74C9AA23602456D4EDD" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="B5B3A82C9DAED9BC200E6E999D06DF46" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor any of the other two species treated here. 
<taxonomicName id="87998FA7A10D55AD0E0BCB6F129EDB0C" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="39008D84592FD96086AB3C11D3BE8346" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in a variety of forest habitats, such as littoral rainforest, tropical dry forest, lowland rainforest, and montane rainforest, and has an altitudinal range of 10 to 1100 m. Despite that most of the material was collected from leaf litter, 
<taxonomicName id="4C885942F51643FC2E925B4AEBCC8C3F" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="5A909136AD8BE99CADC9EEE2C2E56FDE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more likely subterranean in lifestyle, very much like 
<taxonomicName id="70BC8949EFA8CDACC009C1B61608ED4D" authorityName="Hita Garcia &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex curculiformis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curculiformis">
<emphasis id="C912FA8AC15D101910F70E19F4A88249" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex curculiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="898C37C1EE788825DC9709D847847B11" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="624013378E5EF4C163A7F6C0ED557DB6" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="391E30E831D870E46366B061032F25C1" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
<taxonomicName id="AAC8B19DCFABEA4A26747D7FD62CC54E" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="00C3B839444F81FFA030CEC2EF34D559" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most distinctive species of the three treated herein. The shape of the petiole alone separates it very well from 
<taxonomicName id="99CA2BF0577D28EDD750CED7786662DC" authorityName="Hita Garcia &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex curculiformis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curculiformis">
<emphasis id="2F9674BB8621AA99C9B3F85CF57CA485" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex curculiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="973F331F6FF7E1E3C576AA3B5CF47D96" authorityName="Hita Garcia &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex zahamena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zahamena">
<emphasis id="54D3860B15E5A969DBA1A3E9BA080CD5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex zahamena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In these two the petiole is shorter, higher and stronger arched, in profile (without ventral process) around 1.3 to 1.5 times longer than high (LPNeI 127-150), and in dorsal view around 1.4 to 1.6 times longer than broad (DPeI 63-69). By contrast, the petiole of 
<taxonomicName id="CDF216B5A35E850E8051DBC03C6F1D91" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="DA84F6A891B24CFA4408260C5B0ACF24" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively longer, lower, and less arched, in profile (without ventral process) around 1.3 to 1.5 times longer than high (LPNeI 127-150), and in dorsal view around 1.4 to 1.6 times longer than broad (DPeI 63-69).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="444D8D9E9958DF9EE3EAE411101D647B" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="variation">
<paragraph id="8A3AF0E24DFDCFF54CF70565A52E8456" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Variation.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0331692EB0A4731A441D2405616CE251" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
Despite being less variable than previously thought (
<bibRefCitation id="0FE5EAE72C7B552E1882955E605499F0" author="Fisher, BL" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="146 - 152" refId="B7" refString="Fisher, BL, 2007. A new species of Probolomyrmex from Madagascar. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 80: 146 - 152" title="A new species of Probolomyrmex from Madagascar" volume="80" year="2007">Fisher 2007</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="12703B11D8DF1E62D3C2B236E026AD19" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="739EC3D4BAE4A6C8248A13CD1CECD907" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
still displays some noticeable intraspecific variation within a relatively small area in northern Madagascar. The specimens from Makirovana possess a much better developed and conspicuous foveolate surface sculpture than the rest of the material of 
<taxonomicName id="A05E6F677D970FF5FEDC467AEECB71F8" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="ECE42658C81D17671DC3B890BCD1AC19" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most of the material from Makirovana also has a small but distinct metanotal groove, which is absent in the material from other localities, and longer antennal scapes (SI 99-102). These dissimilarities could be used to separate this series as different species. However, there are several good arguments against it. The length of the antennal scapes is always stable within localities, but shows some noticeable geographical variation. The specimens from the type locality possess the shortest scapes (SI 92-94), whereas the ones from Makirovana and Ambondrobe have the longest scapes (SI 99-102). However, the material from Binara and Montagne des 
<normalizedToken id="A290ABA0A16B65CA8DE98D42377DC7EA" originalValue="Français">Francais</normalizedToken>
shows intermediate values (SI 94-96). Furthermore, the metanotal groove is extremely weak in one specimen from Makirovana, almost absent. Also, as mentioned above, surface sculpturing is relatively variable in all three 
<taxonomicName id="FBB33755130002C489D34CDE21F5D631" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9DBDA5A5150C3F404D575D0B8775351B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. So, consequently, we prefer to keep all the material listed as 
<taxonomicName id="A42651ED1F7BE3475F420A39CE790D8C" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Probolomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Probolomyrmex tani" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tani">
<emphasis id="16FCF5191C185F668A33A1F843A969BF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Probolomyrmex tani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as one somewhat variable species.
</paragraph>
